Consider a method like:
```C#
static IEnumerable<U> Select<T,U>(IEnumerable<T> source, Func<T, U> func)
{
    foreach (T item in source)
        yield return func(item);
}
```
For this, the compiler will generate fields equivalent to:
```C#
private int <>1__state;
private U <>2__current;
private int <>l__initialThreadId;
private IEnumerator<T> <>7__wrap1;

private IEnumerable<T> source;
public IEnumerable<T> <>3__source;

private Func<T, U> func;
public Func<T, U> <>3__func;
```
Note the two `Func<T,U>` fields and the two `IEnumerable<T>` fields.  The compiler is generating one set of fields to store the initial arguments to the method, and then another set of fields used as the values of those arguments inside a given enumeration of the enumerable, e.g. the entry point method does this:
```C#
private static IEnumerable<U> Select<T, U>(IEnumerable<T> source, Func<T, U> func)
{
    <Select>d__0<T, U> <Select>d__ = new <Select>d__0<T, U>(-2);
    <Select>d__.<>3__source = source;
    <Select>d__.<>3__func = func;
    return <Select>d__;
}
```
and then `GetEnumerator` does this:
```C#
IEnumerator<U> IEnumerable<U>.GetEnumerator()
{
    <Select>d__0<T, U> <Select>d__;
    if (<>1__state == -2 && <>l__initialThreadId == Environment.CurrentManagedThreadId)
    {
        <>1__state = 0;
        <Select>d__ = this;
    }
    else
    {
        <Select>d__ = new <Select>d__0<T, U>(0);
    }
    <Select>d__.source = <>3__source;
    <Select>d__.func = <>3__func;
    return <Select>d__;
}
```
That duplication makes sense if the body of the iterator overwrites the parameter, since the parameter needs to return to its original value for subsequent enumeration.  But if the parameter is never mutated by the method body, as is the case in this example, such duplication isn't required.  The compiler should be able to detect the lack of such mutation at least in common cases, like reference types, readonly structs, or structs that only have readonly members invoked on them.

In this particular example, such an improvement would end up removing two fields from the iterator object and reducing its size by 16 bytes on 64-bit.

In both async state machines and iterators, the compiler emits a field on the state machine type:
```C#
public int <>1__state;
```
This field is always emitted as an `Int32`.  However, the number of states is typically very small, e.g. one per yield return / await plus a few for known conditions (e.g. -1 for starting / executing, -2 for completed).  It's very rare for the number of states to be larger than, say, 127.  Rather than always using an `Int32`, the compiler could choose to use the smallest data type that will hold all of the values, e.g. if only the states -2 through 40 are needed, it could instead emit the field as:
```C#
public sbyte <>1__state;
```

The benefit of this is _possibly_ smaller state machine objects, depending on what all of the other fields are.  For example, consider a method like LINQ's `Select`:
```C#
static IEnumerable<U> Select<T,U>(IEnumerable<T> source, Func<T, U> func)
{
    foreach (T item in source)
        yield return func(item);
}
```
Today this will produce the following fields on the state machine type:
```C#
private int <>1__state;
private U <>2__current;
private int <>l__initialThreadId;
private IEnumerable<T> source;
public IEnumerable<T> <>3__source;
private Func<T, U> func;
public Func<T, U> <>3__func;
private IEnumerator<T> <>7__wrap1;
```
If we ignore the reference type fields, which will be 4 bytes on 32-bit or 8 bytes on 64-bit, we get:
```C#
private int <>l__initialThreadId;
private int <>1__state;
private U <>2__current;
```
No matter what `U` is, it'll always result in the state machine type being at least 8 bytes larger (on 64-bit) than it would otherwise need to be if it didn't have to store `U`.  But, the `<>1__state` field for this state machine is only ever assigned the values -3, -1, and 1, so the field could instead be an `sbyte`:
```C#
private int <>l__initialThreadId;
private sbyte <>1__state;
private U <>2__current;
```
If it were, and if `U` were <= 3 bytes in size (e.g. if `U` were a `byte` or `char`), then the object wouldn't need to be any bigger to store `U`, as it would be packed to fit into the padding space left from the state, thus reducing the size of the state machine object by 8 bytes on 64-bit.

`B.f` is protected and we shouldn't consider it as implementing the interface.

``` csharp
using System;
interface I
{
    int f();
}
class A
{
    public int f()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Correct  ->  Should be in A.f()");
        return 100;
    }
}
class B : A, I
{
    new protected virtual int f()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Incorrect  ->  Shouldnt be in B.f()");
        return 1;
    }
    static int Main()
    {
        B b = new B();
        I i = b;
        return i.f();
    }
}
```

